h5i declarative output filters
================================

The `*.toml` rule files in this directory, and the engine that runs them
(`src/filter_rules.rs`), are derived from **rtk**:

    rtk — https://github.com/rtk-ai/rtk
    Copyright (c) Patrick Szymkowiak
    Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0

h5i is itself licensed under Apache-2.0 (see the repository LICENSE), so these
files are redistributed under the same license. Per Apache-2.0 §4, this NOTICE
records that the files have been **modified** for use in h5i:

  - The rule files were copied from rtk's `src/filters/*.toml`. Their `[filters.*]`
    schema and inline `[[tests.*]]` golden cases are used as-is or lightly
    adapted; some may diverge from upstream over time.
  - The filter engine was re-implemented in `src/filter_rules.rs` to match rtk's
    8-stage pipeline (strip_ansi → replace → match_output → strip/keep_lines →
    truncate_lines_at → head/tail_lines → max_lines → on_empty) and its
    `strip_ansi`/`truncate` semantics, so the imported golden tests pass.
  - h5i applies these rules only as a fallback within `h5i capture run`, after
    its own coded adapters (pytest/cargo/git) and before the generic scorer;
    h5i always filters the combined stdout+stderr blob, so the `filter_stderr`
    field is accepted but inert.

Upstream rule authorship and copyright remain with the rtk project and its
contributors.

----

h5i's log line-folding (`token_filter::normalize_template` / `summarize_scored`)
is additionally derived from **headroom**:

    headroom — https://github.com/chopratejas/headroom
    Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0

specifically the normalized "dedupe similar" idea (collapse lines that differ
only by numbers/ids into one representative with a count). Only the technique was
reimplemented in Rust; no headroom code was copied.

No code is derived from **context-mode**, which is under the Elastic License 2.0
(source-available, not a permissive OSS license); only generic techniques that
h5i implements independently were considered.
